ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we adopt one step hydrothermal method to synthesize BSA-Au NCs, which is simple and environmentally friendly. The synthesized BSA-Au NCs owns double peaks under the excitation of 390 nm. As the concentration of DOX added increases, the green fluorescence (I

                        510
                     ) increases, while the red fluorescence (I

                        640
                     ) remains unchanged. Based on this, a convenient strategy to detect DOX using ratiometic fluorescence was designed. The developed assay method can be further reliably used for the analytical sensing of DOX in food.

The working principle of our strategy is shown in Fig. 1
                        . Under excitation at 390 nm, the gold clusters synthesized with BSA as the reducing and protective agent has displayed intrinsic two emission peaks at 480 nm and 640 nm, which are originated from BSA and Au NCs, respectively. As the concentration of DOX added increases, the green fluorescence (I

                           510
                        ) increases, while the red fluorescence (I

                           640
                        ) remains unchanged. The emission peak at 510 nm is caused by the red shift of the emission peak at 480 nm of BSA-Au NCs. Based on this, a convenient strategy to detect DOX using ratiometic fluorescence was designed.

Optimizing the reaction conditions of the detection system were conducive to subsequent experiments. In order to make this method applicable to actual detection, we optimized pH and reaction time. The fluorescence intensity ratio (I

                           510

                        /I

                           640

                        ) of the BSA-Au NCs/DOX detection system reaches its maximum at pH = 12 (Fig. 4
                        a). When DOX was added to the BSA-Au NCs solution, the red fluorescence (I

                           640
                        ) remained unchanged. Meanwhile, the green fluorescence (I

                           510
                        ) increased with the reaction time and reached the top and remained stable about 120 sec (Fig. 4b). Therefore, pH as 12 and reaction time as 2 min were selected in the follow-up experiments.
